THE WORK

Real documents from real floors. Not case studies written after the fact. These are the tools I build, the problems I solve, and the systems I leave behind. Everything here was used on the shop floor — not presented in a conference room.

FLOOR
// Built in Toyota City, Japan. Used every day.
HUMAN-MACHINE WORK BALANCE
Yamazumi (積山) magnet board from a Japanese assembly plant. Each color-coded magnet represents a work element — blue for machine time, green for manual work, yellow for walking. This is how Toyota balances work across operators in real time. No software. No spreadsheet. Magnets on a whiteboard, built by the people who do the work, read by the people who manage it.
Human-machine work balance board (積山ボード). Sub-assembly line, 1-bow / 5-bow process. Red notations show takt time targets: 1800 sec, 1600 sec. Written in Japanese by floor operators. This is not a simulation.
A3
// Toyota's single-page problem-solving discipline
あるべき姿 — IDEAL CONDITION PROBLEM SOLVING
The A3 is Toyota's thinking discipline compressed onto a single page. Left side: current condition, investigation, root causes. Right side: ideal condition, countermeasures, action plan. Every engagement I run starts with an A3 and ends with measurable results. These two examples show the method applied to very different problems — steel tube cutting productivity and consumer product assembly transformation.
Steel Tube Manufacturing

Make TSUSA Tube Cutting Great Again

Five steel tube-cutting machines at 40% equipment uptime. Vorne boards silenced. Kanban abandoned. 4M change management gone. In 2018, these machines ran 10,000 recuts per shift. This A3 maps the gap and builds the 12-month action plan to get back — and stay there.

Consumer Products Assembly

BGL Safety, Quality, Productivity Improvement

No lock-out/tag-out. Safety-critical torques not applied. 80% rework from Shanghai. Gas trains built with 7 people that should take 3. This A3 launched the Bluegrass Living Production System — leveled production, one-piece flow, Point & Call built-in quality, Vorne board data collection tied to Acumatica ERP.

STANDARDIZED WORK
// The foundation of every stable process
SEQUENCE OF STEPS (SOS)
Standardized work is the floor's operating system. This Sequence of Steps document defines every action, every torque spec, every quality check, every failure mode — with photos. Built with the operators, not for them. Linked directly to the control plan and PFMEA. When the standard exists, deviation becomes visible. When deviation is visible, problems get solved.
SOS for Front Fascia Bracket installation. Pre-Marriage process, General Assembly. Each step: action, procedure, torque spec, tool, socket, keypoints (Success / Safety / Easy), failure modes, potential effects, quality checks. Revision-controlled, photo-verified.
MIX-MODEL
// Build any product, any sequence, zero changeover
MANIFEST-DRIVEN SEQUENCED PRODUCTION
Mix-model production eliminates dedicated lines. One line builds all variants in any sequence the customer demands. The manifest system I designed uses QR-coded work instructions, symbol-driven flow rack loading, and color-coded part identification — so operators pick the right part for the right unit every time without reading a BOM. This is how Toyota builds Camry, Avalon, and Lexus ES on the same line.
Production Control

Sequenced Manifest System

QR-scanned manifest cards drive the production sequence. Each card specifies part symbols for every operation — operators match symbols to flow rack positions. LH/RH, color variants, manual/electric models all flow in customer-demanded sequence. Zero changeover time.

Material Flow

Symbol-Driven Flow Rack Design

Flow racks designed to match the manifest symbol system. Each position labeled with part category, variant symbol, and return path. Small containers enforce one-piece flow. Sequenced parts (like base covers) loaded in production order. Physical pokayoke — wrong part can't fit wrong position.
